<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,151,1040]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,764,789]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is Latin, 
<taxonomicName box="[562,666,764,788]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pollinosa">
<emphasis box="[562,666,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">pollinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, dusty or pollinose, referring to the general rather heavy pollinosity of the fly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,151,1040]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,836,861]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[338,553,836,860]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pollinosa">
<emphasis box="[338,553,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Sphegina pollinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[698,794,836,860]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pollex">
<emphasis box="[698,794,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">S. pollex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[847,934,836,860]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="culex">
<emphasis box="[847,934,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">S. culex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Male abdominal sternite IV is rather similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[263,352,872,896]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="culex">
<emphasis box="[263,352,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">S. culex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in ventral view and differs from that of 
<taxonomicName box="[815,913,872,896]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pollex">
<emphasis box="[815,913,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">S. pollex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the posterior membranous incision large. Except for the characters mentioned in the key the three species are distinguished by the following characters in the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[397,485,943,968]" captionStart="FIGURE 38" captionStartId="60.[151,250,1528,1550]" captionTargetBox="[249,1337,198,1494]" captionTargetId="figure@60.[231,1356,195,1506]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURE 38. Sphegina (Asiosphegina) pollinosa sp. n. (holotype). A. Genitalia, lateral view. B. Left surstylus, lateral view. C. Left superior lobe, lateral view. D. Tergites III and IV and sternite IV, lateral view. Scale 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/288435/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Figs 38</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[497,527,944,968]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="61.[151,250,1921,1943]" captionTargetBox="[205,1365,781,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@61.[188,1379,769,1885]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURE 39. Sphegina (Asiosphegina) culex sp. n. (holotype). A. Sternite IV, ventral view. B. Left surstylus, lateral view. C. Left superior lobe, lateral view. D. Genitalia, lateral view. Scale 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/288436/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">39</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[540,573,944,968]" captionStart="FIGURE 40" captionStartId="62.[151,250,1380,1402]" captionTargetBox="[223,1356,207,1349]" captionTargetId="figure@62.[215,1371,193,1358]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURE 40. Sphegina (Asiosphegina) pollex sp. n. (holotype). A. Posterior part of sternite IV, ventral view. B. Left surstylus, lateral view. C. Left superior lobe, lateral view. D. Genitalia, lateral view. Scale 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/288437/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<number box="[540,573,944,968]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" value="40.0">40</number>
</figureCitation>
): in 
<taxonomicName box="[622,756,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pollinosa">
<emphasis box="[622,756,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">S. pollinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the dorsal lobe of surstylus is much broader than in the two others, and like 
<taxonomicName box="[334,423,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="culex">
<emphasis box="[334,423,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">S. culex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks a subbasal medio-dorsal thumb-like sublobe (present in 
<taxonomicName box="[1136,1234,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pollex">
<emphasis box="[1136,1234,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">S. pollex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the superior lobe is unusual, composed of several sclerites (usual and simple in the two others).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
